50|$|Many <b>famines</b> {{are caused}} by {{imbalance}} of food production compared to the large populations of countries whose population exceeds the regional carrying capacity. Historically, <b>famines</b> have occurred from agricultural problems such as drought, crop failure, or pestilence. Changing weather patterns, the ineffectiveness of medieval governments in dealing with crises, wars, and epidemic diseases such as the Black Death helped to cause hundreds of <b>famines</b> in Europe during the Middle Ages, including 95 in Britain and 75 in France. In France, the Hundred Years' War, crop failures and epidemics reduced the population by two-thirds.|$|R
50|$|Japan {{experienced}} more than 130 <b>famines</b> between 1603 and 1868.|$|R
